I'm not sure if it's my place to comment since i'm not an admin and since not all '24 admins are here, but i've noticed that a lot of times for situations where someone is in disagreement, current students (admins included) tend to argue for their point, which is expected especially with what happened with sritty. however, that might not actually be the best for the server, since it escalates rather than diffuses the situation. please keep that in mind for the future. Also, for future reference, i think it may be good to include a rules section-- i can copy paste some rules from servers that i'm in as an example. even if people should be decent human beings already, the truth is that they're not, and having a physical rulesset that people are forced to read usually curbs them if they're actually homophobic/racist/whatever.

And in general, if someone IS saying shit like calling someone a foid, it doesn't help anyone to respond in anger. just DM them to say please don't call people that, and tell them they will be banned if it happens again. it's not your place to tell them it's morally wrong or change how they see the world, as long as it doesn't happen in the server.
Usually the more detached you are, the more successful it will be, since again the goal isn't to make sure everyone in the server is an upstanding citizen, as long as there's no fights and stuff.

and concerning Sritty-- he's likely an admitted student. please DM him to tell him (non-angrily) why he's been banned from the server and to let him know to not do that again (if you're planning to let him back in, which honestly, may not be a bad idea to smooth things over once this calms down). and if he does shit again, banning him would not be out of place.
i'm almost certain that he did not know that saying foid will get him banned, and now he is likely being mad and calling cmu discord a bunch of snowflakes (or the like) as he is prob pissed about it
I'll bring up adding a rules section, at this size of the server I'm starting to think it's probably good to have

I think the main issue came with the sheer number of people who tried to engage with him
